  <h1>The 47th Problem</h1>

  <p>
    The 47th Problem refers to Euclid's 47th Proposition, commonly known as the
    Pythagorean Theorem. Within philosophical, educational, and symbolic traditions,
    it has been used to represent the relationship between knowledge, measurement,
    structure, and understanding.
  </p>

  <p>
    The theorem demonstrates how separate elements can form a unified whole.
    Because of this, many traditions have viewed it as a symbol of balance,
    harmony, and the search for truth through observation and reason.
  </p>

  <h2>Geometry and Meaning</h2>

  <p>
    The 47th Proposition has historically been associated with geometry,
    architecture, measurement, and disciplined thinking. Its symbolic value comes
    from the idea that mathematics can reveal order, proportion, and pattern.
  </p>

  <h2>4 and 7</h2>

  <p>
    Religiously and symbolically, 4 often appears as structure: four directions,
    four corners, four seasons, and earthly order. The number 7 often appears as
    completion or sacred fullness, such as seven days, seven heavens in some
    traditions, and sevenfold spiritual patterns.
  </p>

  <div class="quote-box">
    <h2>47 Through RAK47</h2>

    <p>
      For RAK47, the number 47 represents a balance between foundation and vision.
      The 4 symbolizes discipline, structure, craftsmanship, and the work required
      to create something lasting. The 7 symbolizes awareness, intuition,
      perspective, and the search for meaning.
    </p>

    <p>
      Together, 47 becomes a creative philosophy: build with precision, create with
      purpose, and move with vision.
    </p>
